{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cf6a05e4-6527-448c-9ef3-9955fdd3648f","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your .NET crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\n## Analyzing a .NET Crash Dump\n\n**Recommended tools:**\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform, easiest)\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump  # if not installed\n   dotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n   ```\n   Then inside the REPL:\n   - `clrstack` — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n   - `pe` — print the last exception\n   - `dumpheap -stat` — heap overview\n   - `threads` — list all threads\n   - `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect other threads\n\n2. **`lldb` + SOS** (Linux, more powerful)\n3. **WinDbg + SOS** (Windows, full-featured)\n\n**Typical investigation flow:**\n1. Run `pe` to see if there's an unhandled exception\n2. Run `threads` to find the faulting thread\n3. Run `clrstack` on that thread for the managed stack trace\n4. Use `clrstack -a` to see local variables\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running any of these commands on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"87bfec6d-0025-48c6-aa28-f664b324afd5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET application. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their crash dump.","outputTokens":441,"requestId":"CB11:FB5EA:1F1052F:2260A28:6A052B22"},"id":"3cb4a62f-5e22-45b6-b188-122850386385","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:53:50.110Z","parentId":"35a1ddd3-df0f-4723-a5e3-64ddd11c104b"}
